Introduction

Background Information

Basketball is primarily a 5 on 5 team based game. Each team will have a Point Guard (PG), Shooting guard (SG), Small Forward (SF), Power Forward (PF), and a Center (C). The main way of scoring points are a field goals, which consist of 2 pointers and 3 pointers. As well as free throws, which consist of 1 point. the main defensive statistics are Blocks, Steals, and Defensive Rebounds.

A Point Guards (PG) main roll is to be the general of the team, also known as the play-maker. PG’s tend to be the smallest player on the court with high basketball IQ. they tend to have good ball handling skills and are usually fast, Resulting in high number of assist and 2 point field goals.

A Shooting Guard (SG) are shooting specialist, mainly focusing on perimeter shooting. excelling in mid-range shots and 3-point field goals.

A Small Forward (SF) are the jack of all trades, as they as they can score anywhere on the court. They are usually quick and strong, with the ability to drive into the paint and score points, and are able to draw fouls for a potential “and 1” play.

A Power Forward (PF) are considered good scoring option when they are close to the rim, as they tend to be the most explosive player on the court. PF’s tend to have a good Post game, drawing in multiple opposition player, to create open shots for their teammates. They should also have good defensive abilities as they play close to the rim.

A Center (C) have similar traits to a PF, however, a key difference is that they tend to be the tallest and strongest players of the court.

Scenario

As the Chicago Bull finished at an overall ranking of 27 out of 30 teams in the 2018-19 NBA season with a Record of 22 wins and 60 Losses. Due to the teams poor performance, they have been allocated a budget of $118 million for player contacts. This is low compared to the Portland trailblazers who have the largest budget of $140 million. While the team with the best record in league in the 2018-19 season were allocated $131 million.

Aim of the Project

With an allocated budget of $118 Million, we are tasked to find the best potential starting 5 for the 2019-20 NBA season. However, the $118 Million budget is for recruitment of a full squad and needs to be considered when recruiting players.

Justification and Importance

We want to recruit players in-order to deliver and win an NBA Championship for the City of Chicago. Analyzing players based on their salaries and the statistics will aid us in determining and identifying hidden gems and clear must haves for the team.

Exploratory Anlysis

Offensive and defensive rating are key metrics when determining and analysing a team potential win in a season. As having both a strong offensive game will lead to more points being scored, and a strong defensive game will result in less points conceded. Therefore, the key metric we will observe are:

  • ORtg (Teams Offensive Rating)
  • DRtg (Teams Defensive Rating)
  • NRtg (Teams Net Rating)
  • TOV% (Teams Turnover Percentage)
##checking offensive rating

The results shows us a value of 0.98 which indicated a strong positive relationship between NRtg and Wins.

As Net Rating has now been determined as an important factor to wins, it would benefit us to look at the Offensive Rating and Defensive Rating measures and the metrics that measure these variables.

The NBA provides and obtains efficiency statistics based on a players individual statistics. These mainly being points, rebounds, assists, blocks, steals, and turnovers, which can be broken into postie and negative traits. Where points and assists are positive offensive traits. Where Rebounds, Steals, and Blocks are positive defensive traits. And where turnovers are negative traits. {1,2,3,4}

Based on this, our focus on offensive traits would be:

  • 3 point shooting percentage (x3Pp)
  • 2 point shooting percentage (x2Pp)
  • Assists (AST)
  • Total Rebounds (TRB)

and the defensive traits would be:

  • Steals (STL)
  • Blocks (BLK)
  • Turnovers (TOV) (a negative emphasis on this variable as this is a loss of possession)

Assumptions

1. The response variable should be continuous (i.e. ratio/interval)

Net Rating is a ratio scale of measurement.

2. There are two or more explanatory variables that are either continuous or categorical

All explanatory variables are continuous.

There should be independence of observations

car::durbinWatsonTest(fit)
##  lag Autocorrelation D-W Statistic p-value
##    1        0.356662      1.237792    0.04
##  Alternative hypothesis: rho != 0

The Durbin-Watson statistic shows a value of 1.24 which indicates that there is no correlation between residuals and are independent.

3. There should be a linear relationship between the response variable and each explanatory variable

car::avPlots(fit)

All explanatory variables have a linear relationship with the response variable.

4. There should be no significant outliers, influential or high leverage points

5. The data needs to show homoscedasticity

res<- residuals(fit)
fitted <- predict(fit)

ggplot(team_statistics, aes(x = fitted, y = res))+
  geom_point(colour = "blue")+
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, colour = "red", linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE, colour = "black")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

There is no clear pattern present; therefor, homoscedasticity is met.

6. The residuals should be normally distributed

#Check for normal distribution, using a histogram 
ggplot(data =NULL, aes(x= res))+
  geom_histogram( colour = "Black", fill = "Blue", binwidth = 1.5)

The data appears to be normally distributed

#We can also check normality through a normal Q-Q plot 
ggplot(data = NULL, aes(sample =res))+
  stat_qq() + stat_qq_line()

The Q-Q Plot shows that the points appear normally distributed

7. There should not be multicollinearity between the explanatory variables

pairs(formula = ~ PTS_PG + REB_PG + AST_PG + STL_PG + 
        BLK_PG + TOV_PG, data = team_statistics)

There are no clear relationships between the explanatory variables; therefor, the assumption has been met.

Model Testing

The model we are using is:

Net Rating: -66.2 + 0.338(PTS_PG) + 0.779(REB_PG) + 0.367(AST_PG) + 0.691(STL_PG) + 1.53(BLK_PG) - 2.03(TOV_PG)

Player Metrics

Calculate the number of minutes each team played per game on average across the league.

min_PG <- team_statistics %>%
  group_by(Team) %>%
  summarise(min_PG = (MP/G)) %>%
  pull(min_PG) %>%
  mean 

min_PG
## [1] 241.6463

Creating new statistics per game for each player while adjusting the average minutes played per game

players <- player_stat %>%
  group_by(player_name) %>%
  summarise(G = sum(MP) / min_PG,
            PTS_PG = sum(PTS) / G,
            REB_PG = sum(TRB) / G,
            AST_PG= sum(AST) / G, 
            STL_PG = sum(STL) / G,
            BLK_PG = sum(BLK) / G,
            TOV_PG = sum(TOV) / G,
            MP = sum(MP)) %>%
  filter(MP >= 200) %>%
  select(-G)

Expected Net Rating Per Player

We need to calculate player-specific expected net rating.

The expected net rating metric can be interpreted as the net effect we expect a player has on the overall score if the player plays at his best.

players <- mutate(players, exp_NRtg = predict(fit, newdata = players))
